# ERP module context (caveman)

- Path: Modules/ERP only.
- Root rules = base law. Always follow.
- This file = extra ERP law.

- Focus ERP domain: orders, invoices, accounting, operations.
- Keep ERP boundaries clean.
- Reuse Core shared pieces before creating new ones.
- Touch other modules only when user asks.

## Current architecture truth

- ERP is not a demo module. Treat it as an enterprise ERP slice: operational documents and fiscal/accounting documents are related but not interchangeable.
- Physical logistics uses orders, DDTs, goods receipts, stock movements, and returned quantities.
- Fiscal/accounting correction uses invoices and invoice lines as the source of prices and legal references.
- Customer return credit notes must price from source sales `InvoiceLine`; `ReturnOrderLine.unit_price` is only a manual override.
- Supplier return debit notes must price from source purchase `InvoiceLine`; `SupplierReturnLine.purchase_order_line_id` remains logistics lineage only.
- Do not put prices on DDT lines. DDT/bolle lines remain quantity/source-link documents.
- New ERP schema/test code must use `Modules\ERP\Enums\ERPTables` and physical `erp_*` table names.
- Portable migrations matter: MySQL/MariaDB, PostgreSQL, Oracle, and SQLite. Prefer Laravel schema builder and `ERPMigrateUtils` helpers; avoid vendor-specific SQL unless guarded.
- Money, quantities, prices, and costs use decimals, not integers or floats, when persisted. Validate non-negative values where business rules require it.
- Domain mutations belong in services. Filament actions call services; services own validation, transactions, locks, and side effects.
- Permissions use Core CRUD abilities (`select`, `insert`, `update`, `delete`, etc.) plus explicitly seeded domain abilities only when needed (`post`, `unpost`, `force_post`, `reset`, `unlock`, etc.).

